        <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <h3>Which is better for building a personal knowledge base: Notion or Obsidian?</h3>
    <p>Obsidian is better for personal knowledge management. Its bidirectional linking creates an interconnected web of ideas that the graph view helps you navigate. Notion is better for structured knowledge bases that require databases and team collaboration.</p>
    <h3>Can Notion replace Obsidian for note-taking?</h3>
    <p>Notion can handle basic note-taking but lacks the bidirectional linking and local file storage that makes Obsidian powerful for personal knowledge management. Power users who value data ownership and linking often prefer Obsidian for personal notes while using Notion for team projects.</p>
    <h3>Which app offers better offline access?</h3>
    <p>Obsidian stores everything as local Markdown files, providing full offline access with no internet required. Notion's offline support has improved but is less reliable, especially for databases and shared workspaces.</p>
    <h3>Notion vs Obsidian for team collaboration: Which is better?</h3>
    <p>Notion is significantly better for team collaboration with shared workspaces, permissions, real-time editing, and comments. Obsidian is a personal tool with limited collaboration features, though its markdown files can be shared through sync services.</p>
